** Locators **

1. Cypress locators

Cypress Default Selector Priority from there website
data-cy
data-test
data-testid
data-qa
name
id
class
tag
attributes
nth-child


✔️ Recommended order of cypress locators as follows:
1 data-testid
2 id
3 class
4 contains()
5 CSS attribute selectors

⭐️ using data-testid
cy.get('[data-testid="submit-button"]')
Why Best?
- Stable
- Does not break with UI changes
- Fast
- clear intention

⭐️ using id
cy.get('#username')
Why Good?
- Unique
- Fast
- stable until the developer make any changes

⭐️using class
cy.get('.nav-bar')
Why Acceptable?
- Can be unique
- May change with UI changes
- Fast
- Avoid it if class name changes frequently

⭐️ using contains()
cy.contains('Submit')
Why Acceptable?
- Human readable
- May break with UI text changes
- Slower than other locators

⭐️ using CSS attribute selectors
cy.get('input[type="text"]')
Why Acceptable?
- Flexible
- May break with attribute changes
- Moderate speed

What to AVOID in Cypress

❌ Long CSS chains
❌ UI-style related class names (.mt-4 .flex-center)
❌ XPath (Cypress doesn’t support by default)
❌ Text-only selectors (unless intentional)

INTERVIEW ANSWER (Use THIS Version — Salesforce Level)

“In Cypress, I follow the official selector priority:
data-cy, data-test, data-testid, data-qa, name, id, class, tag, and attribute selectors.
My first preference is always test IDs because they are stable and independent of UI layout.
I avoid brittle selectors like nth-child or styling classes, and I rely on semantic attributes wherever possible.”

This answer is PERFECT — short, authoritative, senior-level.

